defaultResolution or Statute?default16.
default 
defaultW
defaultould a War Powers Resolution constitute a real legal limitation on prerogative powers? 
defaultThe reform proposal that was due to be laid before Parliament for approval before the general election in May 2010, 
defaulttook 
defaultthe form of a non-binding war powers resolution,
default  giving the Prime Minister maximum flexibility as to the timing of seeking approval from the House of Commons for a Government decision authorising the use of force by British armed forces outside the UK. As with the invasion of Iraq in 2003, this may mean that the timing of the vote will be such as to ensure that it is too late for the House of Commons to realistically say no. In addition, under the draft resolution, there would have been no need for the Government to seek retrospective approval when the operation 
defaultwas
default urgent or secret. Furthermore, the proposed resolution would not have required the Attorney General 
defaultto 
defaultmake his full advice available to Parliament, though legal reasons would normally be given.  
defaultI
defaultn reality 
defaultthis 
defaultrepresented little change from the current constitutional position and had the added advantage, from the Government’s point of view, of being in a non-
defaultstatutory
