default Many examples could be given to support this. One is Richards J
default 
default in 
defaultThe Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament v The Prime Minister of the United Kingdom
default [2002] EWHC 2777
default at para 59: ‘
defaultA plain purpose of 
defaultthe 
defaultpresent claim is to discourage or inhibit 
defaultthe 
defaultGovernment from using armed force against Iraq without a further Security Council resolution. Thus 
defaultthe 
defaultclaim is an attempt to limit 
defaultthe 
defaultGovernment's freedom of movement in relation to 
defaultthe 
defaultactual use of military force as well as in relation to 
defaultthe 
defaultexercise of diplomatic pressure in advance. That takes it squarely into 
defaultthe 
defaultfields of foreign affairs and defence. In my view it is unthinkable that 
defaultthe 
defaultnational courts would entertain a challenge to a Government decision to declare war or to authorise 
defaultthe 
defaultuse of armed force against a third country. That is a classic example of a non-justiciable decision. I reject Mr Singh's submission that it would be permissible in principle to isolate and rule upon legal issues e.g. as to whether 
defaultthe 
defaultdecision was taken in breach of international law. 
defaultThe 
defaultnature and subject matter of such a decision require it to be treated as an indivisible whole rather than breaking it down into legal, political, military and other components and viewing those components in isolation for 
defaultthe 
defaultpurpose of determining whether they are suited to judicial determination. 
defaultThe 
defaultsame objections of principle apply to an attempt to isolate in advance a potential legal component of a possible future decision with a view to limiting 
defaultthe 
defaultGovernment's freedom of movement when taking 
defaultthe 
defaultdecision itself’.
